{"analysis":"The query aggregates total_amount by the has_campaign flag across fct_orders. On non-campaign days, the average order value (AOV) is 12,616.93 across 1,834 orders, while on campaign days the AOV is 9,693.25 across 484 orders. The campaign-day AOV is approximately 2,923.68 lower than non-campaign days, a relative decrease of about 23.2%.

The direction of the difference aligns with the hypothesis: AOV on discount campaign days is indeed lower than on non-campaign days. The sample sizes (1,834 vs 484) are reasonably large, making the observed difference unlikely to be pure noise, though without variance/standard deviation we cannot compute a formal significance test here. Still, a ~23% gap on hundreds of orders is a substantial and directionally clear signal.

One caveat: the hypothesis implicitly concerns a causal framing (discounts lowering order value), whereas this query is purely observational and does not control for confounders such as product mix, seasonality, or customer segment. The data supports the descriptive claim that campaign-day AOV is lower, which is what the hypothesis states.","verdict":"supported","evidence_summary":"Campaign-day AOV (9,693.25) is ~23% lower than non-campaign-day AOV (12,616.93) across 484 vs 1,834 orders, matching the hypothesis direction."}
